      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush, the Late Bloomer</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William W Goetz letter comments on July 22 profile of Gov George W Bush</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''After Yale, Bush Ambled Amiably Into His Future'' (front page, July 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''After Yale, Bush Ambled Amiably Into His Future'' (front page, July 22):</p>
        <p>George W. Bush blithely dismisses his early absence of focus, saying ''I was young and irresponsible'' and without plans, but ''that's just the way it was.''</p>
        <p>His educational program for schoolchildren, however, includes no such indulgence. There will be strict standards, accountability, discipline and no social promotion.</p>
        <p>Now Mr. Bush has turned out to be a productive and good citizen and may even become a good president. This does not surprise teachers who know all about the the unpredictability of the maturing process and ''late bloomers.''</p>
        <p>Before failing students are assigned to academic oblivion, I would hope that Mr. Bush would exercise some of his much publicized ''compassion'' and consider that there may be some who need to ''amble'' a bit.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM W. GOETZ  Bedminster, N.J., July 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired public school teacher.</p>
      </block>
